The Runge-Lenz vector 

Here we explore further the remarkable property that the closed
orbits for the nontrivial D6-brane system, described by the
lagrangian, (), are identical to the orbits for the
standard nonrelativistic  central force problem.

For the nonrelativistic Kepler problem, the fact that the orbits
are closed ellipses which do not precess is reflected by the
existence of an extra conserved quantity: the Laplace-Runge-Lenz
vector. Normally the existence of this vector is considered to be
a special consequence of the  potential, which is not shared
by other central-force potentials.

Nonetheless, despite the fact that the D6-brane Lagrangian
contains many relativistic corrections as well as a potential
which is not purely proportional to , its orbits are also
non-precessing ellipses. One might therefore wonder whether in
this case there is also a generalised Runge-Lenz vector whose
conservation ensures the absence of precession. We show in this
section, by explicit construction, that the answer to this
question is 'yes'.

Since there are 3 spatial dimensions transverse to the D6 brane in
10 dimensions, it is convenient to phrase the analysis using the
angular momentum vector, which is dual to the conserved
antisymmetric tensor. Let us therefore consider the vector:

      d dt (
